**Markdown Header and List Formatting:**

Here's an example of how to format a header and a list in markdown:

**Header:**
```
# My Header
```
**List:**
```
* Item 1
* Item 2
* Item 3
```
**Markdown Text:**
```
# My Header
Here is a list:

* Item 1
* Item 2
* Item 3
```
**HTML Output:**
```
<h1>My Header</h1>
Here is a list:

<ul>
	<li>Item 1</li>
	<li>Item 2</li>
	<li>Item 3</li>
</ul>
```
**C++ Function:**
```
#include <string>
#include <iostream>
#include <boost/algorithm/string.hpp>

std::string convertMarkdownToHTML(const std::string& markdown) {
	std::string html;

	// Remove any leading or trailing spaces
	markdown = boost::trim(markdown);

	// Split the markdown into individual lines
	std::vector<std::string> lines;
	boost::split(lines, markdown, boost::is_any_of("\n"));

	// Iterate through each line and convert it to HTML
	for (auto& line : lines) {
		if (line[0] == '#') {
			html += "<h" + std::to_string(line[1] - '0') + ">";
			html += boost::trim_copy(line.substr(2));
			html += "</h" + std::to_string(line[1] - '0') + ">\n";
		} else if (line[0] == '*') {
			html += "<ul>\n";
			for (auto& item : boost::split(line, "*", boost::is_any_of(" "))) {
				html += "<li>";
				html += boost::trim_copy(item);
				html += "</li>\n";
			}
			html += "</ul>\n";
		} else {
			html += boost::trim_copy(line) + "\n";
		}
	}

	return html;
}
```
This function takes a reference to a std::string containing markdown formatted text and returns a std::string containing html formatted text. It uses the Boost library to perform the string manipulation.

